If a conforming mesh of Ωx is available, then ﬁnite-dimensional subsets of V1 and V2 can be constructed such that v1 = v2 and w1 = w2 on ΓI. In that case, all boundary terms of (7.3) are zero. The challenge, however, is that Ωx and ΓI are time-dependent. To address this challenge, we work within Chapter 4’s framework for conservation laws on deforming domains. The most expedient approach to obtain conforming ﬂuid and structure function spaces is to construct them once on a static reference domain, Ωy, with vˆ = v on the subset corresponding to the solid subproblem, so that the velocity of ΓI will be vˆ, and the mesh of Ωy will track the ﬂuid–structure interface as it deforms. In most problems, φˆ in Ω1 will then continuously interpolate between the material motion φ in Ω2 and some external boundaries of Ω1 which do not follow the material. This leads to a nonzero vˆ throughout Ω1, which is not uniquely determined by the physics of the FSI problem; practical methods for constructing such a φˆ remain an active area of research in computational FSI, although the most common is to solve a ﬁctitious elasticity problem on Ω1, as will be done in the example implementation of this section.
